'''Ashlee Adams Crews''' (born September 22, 1976) is an American fiction writer who typically incorporates her rural Middle Georgia roots in her works of literature. 

==Biography==
Crews was born and raised just outside of [[Sandersville, Georgia|Sandersville]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. The city promotes itself as <U+201C>the Kaolin Capital of the World<U+201D>, in recognition of one of Georgia<U+2019>s most important minerals, kaolin, a white, alumina-silicate clay.<ref>[http://www.sandersville.net/KaolinCapitaloftheWorld.cfm| Official website - City of Sandersville, Georgia]</ref> Crews earned an English degree from the [[University of Georgia]] and later earned an MFA in Creative Writing<ref name="georgia">{{cite web|url=http://graduate.gcsu.edu/futurestudents/programs/mfa/alumninews|title=Alumni News|work=Georgia College|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> from [[Georgia College and State University]]. She currently lives in [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], [[North Carolina]], with her husband and daughter and has taught composition at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].

The fictionalized version of her hometown plays a key role in many of her stories as her characters seek to find a sense of home somewhere between the place they know and the greater world that they seek to discover.

Ashlee Crews has published several short stories and is currently writing her first novel. Her story <U+201C>Bird Feed<U+201D> appears in [[McSweeney<U+2019>s]] issue #27<ref>https://store.mcsweeneys.net/products/mcsweeneys-issue-27</ref>  and won a [[Pushcart Prize]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pushcart Prize|year=2010|url=http://www.phoenixpubliclibrary.org/controller.jsp?R=1017216}}</ref> <U+201C>Called Out<U+201D> appears in [[The Southern Review]], Autumn 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsu.edu/thesouthernreview/OurLibrary.html|title=Our Library - The Southern Review|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> Her story <U+201C>Bull of the Woods<U+201D> appears in [[Prairie Schooner]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prairieschooner.unl.edu/archives/summer11/summer2011_contributors.html|title=Summer 2011 contributors|work=Prairie Schooner|publisher=University of Nebraska-Lincoln|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> Summer 2011. Her story <U+201C>Restoration<U+201D><ref>{{cite web|title=Shenandoah, Issue 61, Number 2|url=http://shenandoahliterary.org/612/}}</ref> was published in [[Shenandoah (magazine)|Shenandoah]] in February 2012.

Her story "Church Time" won the 2011 James Hurst Prize for Fiction,<ref>{{cite web|title=James Hurst Prize for Fiction|url=http://english.chass.ncsu.edu/creativewriting/story_contest.php}}</ref> sponsored by [[North Carolina State University]] and judged by [[Ron Rash]]. "Church Time" was published by [[Southwest Review]] in Volume 98, Number 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southwest Review, Volume 98, Number 1|url=http://smu.edu/southwestreview/981%20Contents.pdf}}</ref>

Her short story collection "Called Out" was named a finalist for the 2012 [[Flannery O'Connor Award for Short Fiction]].<ref>{{cite web|title=UGA Press Blogspot|url=http://ugapress.blogspot.com/2012/09/winners-announced-for-flannery-oconnor.html}}</ref>

Crews was named a 2013 winner of the Rona Jaffe Foundation<ref>http://www.ronajaffefoundation.org/</ref> Writers' Award.<ref>http://www.ronajaffefoundation.org/winners.html</ref>

